 for bestpractices and # Training & Meal Planner

## Overview
Design and implement a self-service Training & Meal Planner within LifeOps that allows users to configure personalized training schedules and meal plans aligned to their goals. The page should present an end-to-end workflow: goal selection and constraints, auto-generated plan, weekly calendar assignment for workouts and meals, nutrition summaries, and a grocery list export. The feature must integrate with Health Automation (habit tracking, recovery monitoring, workload balancing, and calendar syncing) and be visually consistent with LifeOps’ HEALTH UI language. All user actions must be explainable, auditable, and reversible, with a robust run/history trail for agent-driven generation and adjustments.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A concentrated workspace for configuring and managing training schedules and meal plans tailored to user goals (e.g., weight loss, muscle gain, endurance, maintenance). It combines plan generation, schedule assignment, nutritional insights, and shopping list creation into a single, cohesive interface.

Goals:
- Enable users to define goals, constraints, and preferences; auto-generate feasible training and meal plans; visualize nutrition summaries; export grocery lists; and perform on-page adjustments with agent-assisted suggestions.
- Tie into Health Automation for habit integration, recovery monitoring, workload balancing, and calendar syncing so plans adapt over time based on real-world data.
- Provide a Weekly Calendar to attach workouts and meals, with drag/drop or quick-swap capabilities and agent suggestions for substitutions.
- Deliver nutrition summaries (macros, calories, micronutrients where applicable) and a Grocery List that aggregates items across planned meals, with export options (CSV/JSON/Clipboard).

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Plan Builder: A central, guided widget to select goals (e.g., fat loss, muscle gain, performance), duration (weeks), dietary constraints (vegetarian, allergies, macros targets), activity level, equipment access, and any hard constraints. Includes an “Auto-Generate Plan” action and an “Agent-Suggest Adjustments” control.
- Weekly Calendar: A grid showing days of the week with time blocks for workouts and meals. Supports adding, swapping, and rescheduling items. Each cell should show a compact summary (icon, title, time, status). Include a “Sync with Calendar” action to push events to user’s calendar.
- Nutrition Summary Panel: Displays daily/weekly totals (calories, protein, carbs, fats) and per-meal breakdown. Visual cues for targets vs. actuals; an optional macro/micronutrient breakdown with small charts.
- Grocery List Export: Aggregated items with quantities by week, ability to export as CSV/JSON or copy to clipboard. Include a “Generate Shopping Route” optional enhancement for in-store navigation.
- Adjustments: In-page item-level adjustments with agent suggestions (swap meals/workouts, adjust portions, modify rest periods) and an “Accept/Reject” flow for agent recommendations.
- Visual guidance: dense, dark UI with card-based panels, elevated surfaces, and subtle depth. Use the provided color palette and typography system. Cards show icon at top, title, and metadata beneath. Data visualizations use the chart styles described in the Visual Style section.

API integrations:
- No external APIs are connected for this prompt. All page interactions, generation, and storage are self-contained or mocked for initial implementation. Data should be structured to easily hook into Health Automation and calendar-synchronization services later.

Connected Pages:
- Health Dashboard: This page will feed performance and workload balance data into the Training & Meal Planner, enabling recovery score integration and workload-aware adjustments.

Connected Features:
- Health Automation: Habit tracking, plan generation, recovery monitoring, and workload balancing via personal data and calendar syncing. Plans can be influenced by calendar events and habit adherence data.

## Components to Build
- Plan Builder Component
  - Props: userGoals, constraints, dietaryPrefs, durationWeeks, activityLevel
  - State: selectedGoals, constraints, generatedPlan, isAutoGenerateOn, agentSuggestions
  - Behavior: validate inputs, trigger plan generation, display explanation prompts for agent actions
- Weekly Calendar Component
  - Props: planItems (workouts, meals), weekStartDate
  - State: calendarGrid, selectedSlot, drag/drop state
  - Behavior: add/edit/delete items, swap items, reschedule, calendar sync toggle
- Nutrition Summary Component
  - Props: dailyTotals, weeklyTotals, targets
  - State: selectedDay or meal breakdown toggle
  - Behavior: render macro/micro totals, charts, comparison to targets
- Grocery List Component
  - Props: mealsForPlan, aggregatedItems
  - State: exportFormat (CSV/JSON/Clipboard), isExporting
  - Behavior: compute aggregated shopping list, provide export/clipboard actions
- Adjustments & Suggestions Panel
  - Props: planState, agentCapabilities
  - State: pendingAdjustments, userApprovals
  - Behavior: present agent-suggested swaps/portions, accept/reject workflow
- Data Visualization Module
  - Charts for nutrition vs. targets, plan adherence over time
  - Reuse minimalistic chart styles from Visual Style
- API/Validation Layer (internal)
  - Validate input shapes, ensure non-null arrays, guard all array ops
  - Normalize API-like responses to safe shapes (e.g., data ?? [])
- Shared UI Primitives
  - Dark elevated Card, Button variations (Primary, Secondary), Inputs, Toggles, Chips, Badges
  - Layout primitives: Sidebar, Top Bar, Breadcrumbs

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack assumptions: React (with TypeScript preferred), state management via React hooks or lightweight context; CSS-in-JS or CSS Modules to align with design tokens.
- Requirements:
  - All array data paths must guard against null/undefined before using .map/.filter/.reduce/.forEach/.find/.some/.every.
  - Use data ?? [] when consuming API-like results; validate with Array.isArray() where appropriate.
  - Initialize all array state with proper defaults: useState<T[]>([]) for arrays; useState<PlanItem[]>([]) etc.
  - Use Optional Chaining for nested API/data access: obj?.property?.nested
  - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- UI/UX:
  - Implement Left Sidebar Navigation with collapsible sections and active state indicator (accent pill #FF3B30)
  - Implement Top Breadcrumb/Bar with section title and lightweight controls
  - Implement Plan Builder as guided steps with real-time validation and “Auto-Generate” capability
  - Implement Weekly Calendar with drag/drop or quick-add flows
  - Implement Nutrition Summary with textual and chart-based insights
  - Implement Grocery List export with multiple formats
  - Ensure keyboard accessibility (focus states, aria labels) and screen reader semantics
- Data handling:
  - Centralize defaulting to safe structures: const items = data ?? []; const list = Array.isArray(data) ? data : []
  - Provide shims for plan generation results to always produce arrays/objects consistent with UI
- Performance:
  - Memoize heavy computations (nutrition totals, grocery aggregation) with useMemo
  - Debounce user inputs where generation or analysis might be expensive
- Accessibility:
  - Color contrast per palette; ARIA roles for nav/menus; descriptive labels for dynamic elements
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for runtime safety guards (ensuring no .map calls on null; proper defaults)
  - UI tests for plan generation flow, calendar interactions, and grocery export

### Backend
- Since the prompt states no external APIs are connected, design the backend interfaces as local stubs or in-memory services to support:
  - Plan generation engine (mock): Accept goals/constraints, return plan structure with workouts and meals
  - Calendar sync interface (mock): Accept plan items to push to a calendar object
  - Grocery aggregation service (mock): Accept planned meals and return aggregated items with quantities
- Data models (in code or mocked):
  - Plan: id, goals, durationWeeks, constraints, meals[], workouts[], nutritionTotals
  - Meal: id, name, calories, macros {protein, carbs, fat}, ingredients[]
  - Workout: id, name, durationMin, intensity, targetCalories
  - GroceryItem: name, quantity, unit, notes
  - ScheduleItem: id, type ('meal'|'workout'), startTime, endTime, referenceId
- Validation:
  - Ensure all API-like responses pass through shape checks: Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Use nullish coalescing for all optional fields

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Plan Builder outputs a plan object; Weekly Calendar consumes plan to render schedule
  - Nutrition Summary derives totals from meals/workouts within the plan
  - Grocery List aggregates ingredients from planned meals
  - Adjustments Panel feeds agent suggestions back into plan with user approvals
- State synchronization:
  - Maintain a single source of truth for the currently active plan in React state or a lightweight store
  - When calendar is synced, reflect results in the plan’s schedule and nutrition context
- Error handling:
  - Graceful fallbacks when data is missing; show user-friendly messages
  - All errors must be logged with traceable context for audit trails

## User Experience Flow
1) On landing, user selects goals and constraints in the Plan Builder (e.g., goal: fat loss; dietary prefs: vegetarian; duration: 8 weeks; equipment: dumbbells).
2) User clicks “Auto-Generate Plan” and optional “Agent-Suggest Adjustments” to view recommended meals and workouts, with explanations.
3) Plan appears as a structured set of workouts and meals; nutrition totals display daily and weekly targets.
4) User switches to the Weekly Calendar to assign or rearrange workouts and meals by day/time; can drag/drop or use quick-add.
5) Nutrition Summary updates in real time as plan changes; the Grocery List auto-updates with aggregated ingredients.
6) User can export Grocery List (CSV/JSON) or copy to clipboard; user can also swap meals/workouts via the Adjustments panel with agent suggestions.
7) If Health Automation is enabled, habit tracking, recovery metrics, and workload balancing influence plan adjustments via agent-assisted prompts; calendar syncing propagates to external calendars.
8) From Health Dashboard, users can view a Workload Balance overview, see recovery scores, and access plan recommendations that align with ongoing projects and calendar commitments.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: (Schema sketches; adapt to actual data layer)
- Plan
  - id: string
  - userId: string
  - goals: string[]
  - durationWeeks: number
  - constraints: {
      dietary: string | null
      allergies: string[]
      equipment: string[]
      macroTargets: { calories?: number; protein?: number; carbs?: number; fat?: number } | null
    }
  - meals: MealPlanItem[]
  - workouts: WorkoutPlanItem[]
  - nutritionTotals: { daily: { calories: number; protein: number; carbs: number; fat: number }[]; weekly: { calories: number; protein: number; carbs: number; fat: number }[] }
  - schedule: ScheduleItem[]
  - groceryList: GroceryItem[]
- Meal
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - calories: number
  - macros: { protein: number; carbs: number; fat: number }
  - ingredients: { name: string; quantity: number; unit: string }[]
- Workout
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - durationMin: number
  - intensity: string
  - targetCalories?: number
- GroceryItem
  - name: string
  - quantity: number
  - unit: string
  - notes?: string
- ScheduleItem
  - id: string
  - type: 'meal' | 'workout'
  - startTime: string (ISO time)
  - endTime?: string
  - referenceId: string (mealId or workoutId)
- UserPreference (optional)
  - includes proneness to scheduling conflicts, preferred meal times, etc.

API Endpoints (mocked or stubbed for internal flow)
- POST /plan/generate
  - Body: { userId, goals, durationWeeks, constraints }
  - Response: Plan object (ensured to include meals/workouts with safe shapes)
- POST /calendar/sync
  - Body: { planId, calendarProvider: 'local'|'google'|'apple', timezone }
  - Response: { success: boolean, nextSync?: string }
- POST /grocery/aggregate
  - Body: { planId }
  - Response: { items: GroceryItem[] }
- POST /plan/adjust
  - Body: { planId, adjustments: Adjustment[] }
  - Response: Plan with updated meals/workouts/schedule
- GET /plan/{planId}
  - Response: Plan or null
- POST /agent/suggest
  - Body: { planId, context }
  - Response: { suggestions: Adjustment[] }

Security
- Authentication: Standard user auth (session/token). Ensure all endpoints and UI actions check isAuthenticated and userRole where applicable.
- Authorization: Users can only read/modify their own plans; admin overrides where necessary but logged.
- Auditability: Each action that mutates a plan must generate an audit trail entry (who, when, what changed, rationale). Plan generation, adjustments, and calendar sync are all recorded.

Validation
- Input validation for all endpoints and UI interactions; ensure:
  - All arrays are guarded: const items = response?.data ?? []
  - Before array methods: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - All optional fields are defaulted safely.
  - Time fields are valid ISO or UI-mapped time values.
- Data normalization: Normalize response shapes to safe defaults to avoid runtime exceptions.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The Plan Builder can produce a complete Plan with at least 2 weeks of meals and workouts, with non-null arrays for meals/workouts.
- [ ] The Weekly Calendar renders all plan items without runtime errors; dragging/swapping updates schedule and persists changes.
- [ ] Nutrition Summary shows daily totals and weekly totals with correct aggregation and displays targets; no null/undefined data path crashes.
- [ ] Grocery List aggregates ingredients from all planned meals; export to CSV/JSON works and data matches the on-screen items.
- [ ] Agent Suggestions can be accepted or rejected; adjustments apply to the plan with an audit trail.
- [ ] Calendar Sync action accurately toggles and produces a traceable log entry.
- [ ] All array usages are guarded with nullish defaults; no runtime crashes due to null/undefined arrays.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Dark UI with elevated cards, dense layouts suitable for power users
- Left navigation with collapsible sections and active-state indicators
- Top bar and breadcrumbs for context
- Data visualizations with minimal, high-contrast lines and subdued gridlines
- Interactive controls with consistent typography, spacing, and micro-interactions
- Use of the accent color (#FF3B30) for active indicators and alerts; keep most UI neutral to preserve focus
- Ensure good legibility, accessible controls, and predictable affordances

Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary background: #0B0B0C
- Secondary surface: #151718
- Tertiary surface / panel outline: #1F1F20
- Primary text / headings: #FFFFFF
- Secondary text / meta: #9DA3A6
- Subtle text / disabled: #56595B
