=== TASK ===
# Training & Meal Planner

## Overview
Design and implement a self-service Training & Meal Planner within LifeOps that allows users to configure personalized training schedules and meal plans aligned to their goals. The page should present an end-to-end workflow: goal selection and constraints, auto-generated plan, weekly calendar assignment for workouts and meals, nutrition summaries, and a grocery list export. The feature must integrate with Health Automation (habit tracking, recovery monitoring, workload balancing, and calendar syncing) and be visually consistent with LifeOps’ HEALTH UI language. All user actions must be explainable, auditable, and reversible, with a robust run/history trail for agent-driven generation and adjustments.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A concentrated workspace for configuring and managing training schedules and meal plans tailored to user goals (e.g., weight loss, muscle gain, endurance, maintenance). It combines plan generation, schedule assignment, nutritional insights, and shopping list creation into a single, cohesive interface.

Goals:
- Enable users to define goals, constraints, and preferences; auto-generate feasible training and meal plans; visualize nutrition summaries; export grocery lists; and perform on-page adjustments with agent-assisted suggestions.
- Tie into Health Automation for habit integration, recovery monitoring, workload balancing, and calendar syncing so plans adapt over time based on real-world data.
- Provide a Weekly Calendar to attach workouts and meals, with drag/drop or quick-swap capabilities and agent suggestions for substitutions.
- Deliver nutrition summaries (macros, calories, micronutrients where applicable) and a Grocery List that aggregates items across planned meals, with export options (CSV/JSON/Clipboard).

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Plan Builder: A central, guided widget to select goals (e.g., fat loss, muscle gain, performance), duration (weeks), dietary constraints (vegetarian, allergies, macros targets), activity level, equipment access, and any hard constraints. Includes an “Auto-Generate Plan” action and an “Agent-Suggest Adjustments” control.
- Weekly Calendar: A grid showing days of the week with time blocks for workouts and meals. Supports adding, swapping, and rescheduling items. Each cell should show a compact summary (icon, title, time, status). Include a “Sync with Calendar” action to push events to user’s calendar.
- Nutrition Summary Panel: Displays daily/weekly totals (calories, protein, carbs, fats) and per-meal breakdown. Visual cues for targets vs. actuals; an optional macro/micronutrient breakdown with small charts.
- Grocery List Export: Aggregated items with quantities by week, ability to export as CSV/JSON or copy to clipboard. Include a “Generate Shopping Route” optional enhancement for in-store navigation.
- Adjustments: In-page item-level adjustments with agent suggestions (swap meals/workouts, adjust portions, modify rest periods) and an “Accept/Reject” flow for agent recommendations.
- Visual guidance: dense, dark UI with card-based panels, elevated surfaces, and subtle depth. Use the provided color palette and typography system. Cards show icon at top, title, and metadata beneath. Data visualizations use the chart styles described in the Visual Style section.

API integrations:
- No external APIs are connected for this prompt. All page interactions, generation, and storage are self-contained or mocked for initial implementation. Data should be structured to easily hook into Health Automation and calendar-synchronization services later.

Connected Pages:
- Health Dashboard: This page will feed performance and workload balance data into the Training & Meal Planner, enabling recovery score integration and workload-aware adjustments.

Connected Features:
- Health Automation: Habit tracking, plan generation, recovery monitoring, and workload balancing via personal data and calendar syncing. Plans can be influenced by calendar events and habit adherence data.

